      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im doing a bit of a deep dive into 21st century politics for a project. how would modern historians generally view if the UN has actually been effective at preventing major conflicts lately?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Modern historians largely view the United Nations as having become more effective at containment and diplomatic de-escalation rather than militarily preventing conflicts since the Cold War. While the UN has largely avoided the catastrophic engagement levels of World War II through robust peacekeeping and sanctions, major regional wars like Myanmar's civil war or the Syrian conflict continue to persist, leading scholars to argue its power is increasingly limited by the lack of a standing enforcement army. Consequently, the prevailing academic consensus is that the UN excels at creating temporary ceasefires and facilitating dialogue, but it struggles to sustain long-term peace without major member state buy-in. Ultimately, its legacy is seen as one of sophisticated diplomatic management that has prevented even worse outcomes globally, even as it fails to stop the frequency of local violent outbreaks entirely.",
